  <header class="consulting-head">
    <h1>Work with me</h1>
  </header>

  <section class="consulting-section consulting-thesis">
    <p>I&rsquo;ve specialized in being a generalist. Some engagements start when a team is trying to figure out a strategy and the situation isn&rsquo;t clear yet. Some start when a program is already running and a team can&rsquo;t tell what is actually happening. Most of my work to date has been in global health and institutional research.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="consulting-section consulting-wounds">
    <ul class="wounds-list">
      <li>A procedure formally vested with decision-making authority that does not, in fact, produce the decisions. The decisions are produced by a different, unnamed procedure.<span class="wound-aka">AKA <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decoupling" rel="noopener">decoupling</a> (Meyer &amp; Rowan, 1977).</span></li>
      <li>A failure distributed across multiple participants such that each can procedurally attribute it to another. The whole has no attributable participant.<span class="wound-aka">AKA the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Problem_of_many_hands" rel="noopener">problem of many hands</a> (Thompson, 1980).</span></li>
      <li>An indicator that improves while the encounter, outcome, or relationship it was supposed to protect does not. Naming the divergence is structurally indistinguishable from opposing measurement.<span class="wound-aka">AKA <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goodhart%27s_law" rel="noopener">Goodhart&rsquo;s law</a> (1975).</span></li>
      <li>A program whose obsolescence is recognized by all parties (including the original funder) but whose discontinuation would require one of them to formally acknowledge the original commitment as a misallocation.<span class="wound-aka">AKA <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Escalation_of_commitment" rel="noopener">escalation of commitment</a> (Staw, 1976).</span></li>
      <li>A speaker whose public statement must be defensible rather than accurate. The accurate version is structurally weaker than the defensible one.<span class="wound-aka">AKA <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Strategic_ambiguity" rel="noopener">strategic ambiguity</a> (Eisenberg, 1984).</span></li>
      <li>A program whose continuity depends on a specific individual. The dependency exists because the individual's contribution was never documented.<span class="wound-aka">AKA the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bus_factor" rel="noopener">bus factor</a>.</span></li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="consulting-section consulting-getting-started">
    <h2>Getting started</h2>
    <p>If you would like to work together, send me a short or long note about the problem you are working on. I will ask a few follow-up questions to figure out whether I can be useful before either of us puts time or money down. The more context you share, the better I can prepare, and the more useful the first conversation will be. I usually reply within a few days; first calls typically happen within a week or two.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="consulting-section consulting-essay-invitation">
    <p>If you&rsquo;d like to read more before our first call, <a href="/consider-the-tree/">Consider the Tree</a> is the longer written version of how I work.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="consulting-section consulting-working-with-me">
    <h2>Working with me</h2>
    <p>Most engagements start with a paid thought-sparring conversation: <strong>$350 for a 60–90 minute call</strong>. I send a few prep questions a day or two ahead. The call is where I work out whether I can be useful to the situation, and where you work out whether you want to keep going.</p>
    <p>Within a few days after the call, you get a short written follow-up: what I would actually do, what I would want to know more about, and whether I think I am a fit. If we keep going, we agree scope and rate in writing &ndash; usually a fixed-fee deliverable or an hourly block, your preference.</p>
    <p>If $350 is too much, write anyway. Rate flexes for early-stage or public-interest work. I usually have capacity for one or two new engagements at a time.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="consulting-section consulting-deliverables">
    <p>Not every engagement ends in a deliverable. When there is one, it usually takes one of these shapes:</p>
    <ul class="deliverables-list">
      <li>Synthesis memos (5&ndash;15 pages) on a question your team can't get clean on, usually after several meetings that haven't converged.</li>
      <li>Program audits. What's working, what's reported as working, where the two diverge. Confidential.</li>
      <li>Problem-framing memos for grant proposals, before the drafting starts. Most proposals that fail in writing failed in framing two weeks earlier.</li>
      <li>Workshop facilitation when a team has been stuck on the same disagreement across more than one meeting.</li>
      <li>Draft text. Policy, IRB, protocol, manuscript framing, board memos. I produce the first draft; you take it from there.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

